Tutorial 3 - Enhancing Your Typescript Knowledge

Tutorial 3 - Enhancing Your Typescript Knowledge

6 steps

In this tutorial, enhance your Typescript knowledge by using interfaces over type declarations and effectively using them in different aspects of your code.

Learn to extend interfaces, create custom type aliases from primitive types, perform type inference and unions, and write enumerations to easily reason your code.

Start your year learning more about Typescript

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Required to have finished Tutorial 1 and Tutorial 2.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Learn how to write custom types and interfaces
  • Extend and inherit from existing types and interfaces
  • Use between union types and enumerations

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Types in Typescript

    Remember that you have to use the same project since Tutorial 1. If you haven't yet, please go back and start on Tutorial 1.

    At this point, you have to learn about types in Typescript in the context of using the type keyword and writing custom types. Do note that this terminology for types can mean anything from enums, class objects (classes), and interfaces (which is covered in the next step).

    Here is a quick check up before proceeding. Your explorer and file structure should look similar to the screenshot below.

    Now, head to the typescript directory and create a new directory called enhanced-knowledge. Head to the enhanced-knowledge directory and create a new file called types.ts.

    In TypeScript, the type keyword is used to define custom types. These can be used for creating more specific and reusable type definitions. Here are some of the different types you can define using the type keyword:

    type Meter = number;
type UserInput = string;
type Maybe = boolean;
    TypeScript

    Write this on your new file types.ts.

    They are best used to define user inputs such as logging in and registering. For example, the following custom types are used to define what could be the user input for logging in.

    type LoginInput = {
	email: string,
	username: string,
	id: number
}
    TypeScript

    Typescript also supports unions. A union type allows you to define a type that can be one of several types. This allows you to define a more dynamic user input e.g. when a user fails to input their email, consider using undefined to denote "empty" input.

    type LoginInput = {
	email: string | undefined,
	username: string,
	id: number
}
    TypeScript

    There is actually a shorthand version for the sometype | undefined where "sometype" can be any type e.g. number, string, or boolean, and that is the following code snippet below.

    type LoginInput = {
	email?: string,
	username: string,
	id: number
}
    TypeScript

    Instead of using string | undefined, the shorthand uses a question mark symbol (?) after the field name to shorten it to, in this example, email?. You can read it as "Will there be a data here of type string? Otherwise, undefined".

  • Step 2: Interfaces in Typescript

    In TypeScript, interfaces are used to define the structure of objects, specifying the shape and types of their properties and methods. An interface can be thought of as a contract for an object that ensures it has specific properties and behaviors.

    Although, developers can still define their "types" with the type and interface keywords, the interface keyword to create interfaces is more flexible as you can extend from one interface to another.

    In the same enhanced-knowledge directory, create a new file called interfaces.ts. Write the following code to the file.

    interface Name {
	firstName: string,
	lastName: string,
	middlename: string | undefined 
}
    TypeScript

    At first, you might want to think, "oh this can just be written with the type keyword". But what if you want to extend the properties for another? You can't do that with the type keyword. You can do it with the interface keyword.

    Much like class objects, you can use the extends keyword to extend and reuse a definition of an interface.

    For example, let's say you want to have other details by extending the Name interface such as parents, status, and address. See the following code below and write it down on the file interfaces.ts.

    interface Person extends Name {
	status: "single" | "married" | "widowed",
	address: string,
	parents: [Person, Person] | undefined
}
    TypeScript

    Let's try declaring a variable using the Person interface. Write this below your new code.

    const person: Person = {
  status: "single",
  address: "",
  parents: undefined,
  middlename: undefined
}
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/enhanced-knowledge/interfaces.ts

    You should get an error that one or two fields are missing. Those fields come from where you extended or more accurately, "inherited" an interface. Those properties mentioned came from the Name interface.

    To resolve the error, just add those missing fields like the code below.

    const person: Person = {
  status: "single",
  address: "",
  parents: undefined,
  middlename: undefined,
  firstName: "",
  lastName: ""
}
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/enhanced-knowledge/interfaces.ts

    The errors should be gone by now.

  • Step 3: More About Union Types in Typescript

    Union types in Typescript allow you to add more possible data types for your inputs for your outputs. You can also use this to define a state.

    Remember the previous code example from the previous step? It actually has this field called status with a defined union type containing values "single", "married" and "widowed".

    A unique part of Typescript is that unlike other languages, union types can be a set of objects. So a string value of "widowed" is part of the set of values for a union. You can even add a number.

    Other types, values (e.g. strings, numbers, objects) that are not part of the union type, will not be considered. Only what was defined as part of the set union are valid values.

    In the same directory, create a new file called unions.ts. Write the following code to the new file.

    type State = "on" | "off";

const status: State = "none";
console.log(status);
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/enhanced-knowledge/unions.ts

    This should throw a compiler error like the screenshot below.

    To resolve, just replace the value "none" with one of the values defined in the union type State such as "on" and "off". Replace the old code with the following corrected version.

    type State = "on" | "off";

const status: State = "on";
console.log(status);
    TypeScript

    This should not error after you run the same command again.

    Although you can use union types to define states, or a set of values grouped together, structures that require mapping and complexity will make you choose enumerations instead. Enumerations will be discussed in the next step.

  • Step 4: Enumerations

    In TypeScript, enums (short for "enumerations") are a way to define a set of named constants. Enums allow you to declare a collection of related values, and they provide a more readable and maintainable way to work with constant values, particularly when these values are logically grouped together.

    For example, take for example your previous code example from the previous step. You can also change it to an enum and it should at least give you the same effect. In the same directory, create a new file called enums.ts. Write the following code snippet below.

    enum State {
	On,  // 0
	Off  // 1
}

const status: State = State.On

console.log(status)
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/enhanced-knowledge/enums.ts

    This should give you an output of "0". Automatically, enums variants e.g. On and Off, will be assigned by number values by default starting at 0. Each enum variant starting at the top gets incremented by 1. Therefore, the output for the following code

    console.log(State.Off)
    TypeScript

    will give you an output of "1" since Off variant is the second variant.

    Fortunately, you can always custom define values for enums. For example, the following code snippet has enums with variants assigned with custom values.

    enum CustomState {
	On = "Activated",
	Off = "Deactivated"
}

const customStatus: CustomState = CustomState.Off
console.log(customStatus)

enum CrazyEnum {
	Off = 15,
	On = "true"
}

const crazyVar: CrazyEnum = CrazyEnum.On
console.log(crazyVar, CrazyEnum.Off)
    TypeScript

    The only limitation with custom values is that you cannot assign a boolean value such as true and false.

    Again, enums are very useful if you want to have a fixed set of related values but slightly complex requirements as compared to union types. Both union types and enums are useful to provide a more meaningful context of your code.

  • Step 5: Apply Your Knowledge

    Let's apply what you have learned so far with Typescript. There is a challenge you need to do and that is to fix the following Javascript code to Typescript code.

    First, at the root directory of your project. Head to the typescript directory. Create a new directory called challenges.

    For this challenge, create a new file called part1.ts. Here is the challenge statement: Given that you are given a function named plus, it should receive two parameters x and y. These two parameters can have a data type that is a number, a string, or an undefined value. Each value can only be used with a + operator if they have the same data type e.g. number can only be operated with a number but not string. However, if either one of the values are undefined, then return undefined.

    Here is the code that you should fix. Write this down to the file part1.ts.

    function plus(x, y) {
	if ((typeof x === "number") && (typeof y === "number")) return x + y;
}

console.log(plus(2025,1))
console.log(plus(undefined, 21));
console.log(plus("StackUp", "Learn"))
    TypeScript

    Once you are confident, run the following commands at the root directory of your project and ensure there are no errors.

    deno fmt
deno run --check typescript/challenges/part1.ts

    If there are no errors, the correct output should be similar to the text below. Attempt to get a similar output with no errors!

    2026
undefined
StackUpLearn
  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    You have reached the end! Now to finish this tutorial, you have to carefully follow Step 5 and check the expected output a screenshot.

    Your screenshot should show:

    • your part1.ts file is visible
    • your file explorer is visible
    • your terminal output should be the same as the example screenshot with the full command shown
    • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)

    If your expected output matches yours, congratulations! You have finished and completed this tutorial
